Quality-adjusted life years (QALYs) are well recognized as a valid measure for 
outcomes in cost-effectiveness analyses. A summary health utility score is 
necessary to evaluate QALYs. The objective of this study was to predict a 
summary utility score (represented by the Health Utility Index [HUI2]) from 
scores on the SF-36.
METHODS: A structural equation framework was applied to longitudinal data 
collected from 1992 to 1995 on a sample of patients insured by Southem 
California Kaiser Permanente (N = 6921). An ordinary least squares (OLS) method 
was used to estimate the HUI2.
