Exercise testing predicts both cardiac events and mortality after age 65, just 
as it does for younger patients. In both age groups, functional aerobic capacity 
itself is a potent indicator of mortality risk. In the elderly, achievement of 
predicted functional aerobic capacity identifies favorable mortality even in the 
presence of CAD and CAD risk factors.

